00:01:16,218 --> 00:01:17,779
like I feel I can empathize with them,

19
00:01:17,799 --> 00:01:18,700
they feel like a person.

20
00:01:19,400 --> 00:01:21,122
I mean, like when was the last time you played a game

21
00:01:21,142 --> 00:01:22,543
where you felt breakable?

22
00:01:23,143 --> 00:01:25,325
And not just breakable, but consequentially so,

23
00:01:25,405 --> 00:01:27,927
where you fear a failure because a failure

24
00:01:27,987 --> 00:01:29,368
is the beginning of something worse.

25
00:01:31,197 --> 00:01:34,280
So human bodies are incredibly diverse in so many ways.

26
00:01:34,420 --> 00:01:36,642
Each of us unique with thoughts and feelings,

27
00:01:36,802 --> 00:01:38,424
strengths and weaknesses of all our own.

28
00:01:38,824 --> 00:01:40,826
Bodies coming in all different shapes, sizes, and colors.

29
00:01:41,367 --> 00:01:42,768
But we have one thing in common

30
00:01:42,848 --> 00:01:44,149
and that's what we're made out of,

31
00:01:44,510 --> 00:01:48,213
which is skin, bone, nerves, blood, meat.

32
00:01:50,315 --> 00:01:50,696
Breakable.

33
00:01:52,677 --> 00:01:53,438
Unless you're Bruce Willis.

34
00:01:54,866 --> 00:01:58,807
But there are a lot of games that disproportionately feature Bruce Willis as a player character.

35
00:01:59,568 --> 00:02:01,649
And don't get me wrong, there's nothing wrong with power fantasies.

36
00:02:02,329 --> 00:02:02,849
I like power.

37
00:02:04,090 --> 00:02:08,711
But power isn't a universally human quality. Moreover, power isn't always interesting.

38
00:02:09,252 --> 00:02:10,492
But being human, I think, is.

39
00:02:12,456 --> 00:02:15,099
So some of you may have noticed that the title of this talk is taken from the

40
00:02:15,139 --> 00:02:17,862
famous short story by Terry Bisson called They're Made Out of Meat,

41
00:02:18,603 --> 00:02:21,706
which recounts a conversation between two aliens marveling over the fact that

42
00:02:21,726 --> 00:02:23,908
the dominant species of life on earth, that is to say,

43
00:02:24,289 --> 00:02:27,872
humans, are made entirely out of meat and communicate by, quote,

44
00:02:28,253 --> 00:02:31,636
flapping their meat at each other, and, quote, squirting air through their meat,

45
00:02:32,417 --> 00:02:33,258
as I am doing right now.

46
00:02:34,525 --> 00:02:38,708
So I read this story when I was like a little kid, and it really enamored me not only with science fiction as a whole,

47
00:02:39,088 --> 00:02:41,569
but the idea of the physicality of humans.

48
00:02:41,870 --> 00:02:46,612
Like, we think, and we feel, and we have like fears and strengths and loves,

49
00:02:46,672 --> 00:02:49,354
and some of us are nervous wrecks, but before any of that,

50
00:02:50,054 --> 00:02:55,257
we're physical beings that have to exist in this world without falling apart.

51
00:02:57,018 --> 00:02:59,640
So how does that work? What physically is a person?

52
00:03:00,300 --> 00:03:01,661
Well, we're a lot of things.

53
00:03:03,041 --> 00:03:09,866
were 206 bones wrapped up in 640 muscles all like weaved through by 40 plus miles of nerves,

54
00:03:10,087 --> 00:03:14,130
some 70 plus organs, all held together by this weird sack that's constantly dying and

55
00:03:14,170 --> 00:03:14,890
replacing itself.

56
00:03:15,851 --> 00:03:18,313
The point I'm trying to make is, we're made out of parts.

57
00:03:19,942 --> 00:03:21,784
Many different parts all working together.

58
00:03:22,284 --> 00:03:23,686
A lot of them we need to stay alive,

59
00:03:23,766 --> 00:03:26,108
but for many of them, their damages and absences

60
00:03:26,128 --> 00:03:27,609
can be adapted to, reckoned with.

61
00:03:28,270 --> 00:03:31,813
The 206 bones, 640 muscles, all that, usually.

62
00:03:31,993 --> 00:03:32,914
That's usually what we are.

63
00:03:33,054 --> 00:03:34,835
But things happen, and we break.

64
00:03:35,716 --> 00:03:37,538
Which brings us to the other thing that we are as humans,

65
00:03:38,459 --> 00:03:39,119
which is fragile.

66
00:03:40,166 --> 00:03:43,447
There are so many things that can go wrong in the human body without much difficulty.

67
00:03:43,507 --> 00:03:45,247
Physical traumas are easy to come by.

68
00:03:45,668 --> 00:03:47,308
Everybody trips, everybody falls,

69
00:03:47,728 --> 00:03:51,269
manage to catch yourself wrong and your arm can take on a whole new shape,

70
00:03:51,469 --> 00:03:53,770
as my brother once learned while he was skating.

71
00:03:54,850 --> 00:03:59,172
Don't catch yourself at all, and a cushion might make you forget the entire concert you just came out of,

72
00:03:59,732 --> 00:04:02,153
as I once learned while coming out of a concert.

73
00:04:03,333 --> 00:04:04,013
And I was fortunate.

74
00:04:04,313 --> 00:04:08,555
If I had hit my head worse, that could have been like the beginning of some very serious problems or an ending altogether.

75
00:04:09,714 --> 00:04:12,355
And that's to say nothing of the effects of extreme heat, cold,

76
00:04:12,695 --> 00:04:15,156
infections, diseases, our irritating need to do things

77
00:04:15,196 --> 00:04:19,358
like eat and sleep. And we live in a world filled with sharp

78
00:04:19,398 --> 00:04:24,540
things, fast things, hard things, long drops. So let's

79
00:04:24,580 --> 00:04:28,461
just not go anywhere or do anything. Because the world is

80
00:04:28,501 --> 00:04:32,283
terrifying. But even that can mess you up. Like

81
00:04:33,666 --> 00:04:36,467
Everybody knows by now that prolonged periods of sitting

82
00:04:36,787 --> 00:04:38,127
will wreck a body over time.

83
00:04:38,187 --> 00:04:40,308
Just like, oh, my legs are dying.

84
00:04:40,888 --> 00:04:46,550
But also, severe damage can be done in even shorter periods

85
00:04:46,570 --> 00:04:46,890
than that.

86
00:04:48,371 --> 00:04:50,971
Dave Mustaine, the lead singer and guitarist for Megadeth,

87
00:04:51,331 --> 00:04:54,572
fell asleep with his arm hanging over the back of a chair

88
00:04:55,213 --> 00:04:56,913
and woke up with severe nerve damage

89
00:04:56,953 --> 00:04:58,494
that took months to repair.

90
00:04:59,634 --> 00:05:01,655
It was like a year before he picked up a guitar again.

91
00:05:03,127 --> 00:05:08,949
But that brings me to my next point about what it's like being meat, which is we do repair and we adapt.

92
00:05:09,830 --> 00:05:11,530
Dave Mustaine's arm nerves got right again.

93
00:05:12,151 --> 00:05:13,992
My brother's arm got arm-shaped again.

94
00:05:14,012 --> 00:05:16,333
Eventually, I did remember that concert.

95
00:05:17,053 --> 00:05:19,334
And our physical forms are incredibly resilient.

96
00:05:20,014 --> 00:05:21,315
But I just said we were fragile.

97
00:05:21,935 --> 00:05:23,036
And now I'm saying we're resilient.

98
00:05:23,296 --> 00:05:24,676
But of course we are. We're all of these things.

99
00:05:25,695 --> 00:05:28,797
For all of our breakable parts and glowing red weak points,

100
00:05:29,217 --> 00:05:32,018
as we have, we're robust, resilient,

101
00:05:32,158 --> 00:05:33,839
and capable of surviving extreme traumas.

102
00:05:34,620 --> 00:05:36,341
Yes, we're made out of parts,

103
00:05:36,641 --> 00:05:38,382
and those parts can fail and be lost,

104
00:05:38,782 --> 00:05:39,803
but the whole continues.

105
00:05:40,263 --> 00:05:41,764
We're fragile and we break easily,

106
00:05:42,084 --> 00:05:43,125
but we can be restored,

107
00:05:43,305 --> 00:05:44,986
and what can't be restored can be adapted to.

108
00:05:46,507 --> 00:05:47,567
So we're made out of parts,

109
00:05:47,788 --> 00:05:49,068
we're fragile, and we're resilient.

110
00:05:49,509 --> 00:05:51,009
And it's the combination of these three elements

111
00:05:51,029 --> 00:05:52,770
which I think comprises the core

112
00:05:53,311 --> 00:05:54,531
of the human physical experience.

113
00:05:55,852 --> 00:05:58,599
take one away and you're left with either superman or a robot

114
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:00,043
or a glass figurine.

115
00:06:00,744 --> 00:06:03,492
So, we're GDC. What's this got to do with video games?

116
00:06:04,653 --> 00:06:10,276
Well, I don't know if you noticed, but a lot of video games feature humans as player characters,

117
00:06:10,656 --> 00:06:11,257
which is pretty neat.

118
00:06:11,717 --> 00:06:12,177
Humans are cool.

119
00:06:12,197 --> 00:06:12,918
I like games.

120
00:06:13,278 --> 00:06:13,938
Let's put them together.

121
00:06:14,999 --> 00:06:18,661
But while I've noticed there's been a push, and justifiably so, for making characters

122
00:06:18,701 --> 00:06:23,324
feel more human in games as far as the right writing them goes and making them behave like

123
00:06:23,344 --> 00:06:28,267
people and be relatable on an emotional level, it's still, I feel, fairly uncommon to see

124
00:06:28,407 --> 00:06:32,450
humans in games represented as truly physical beings, as breakable, as meat.

125
00:06:34,103 --> 00:06:37,184
And I think that as games are trying and making better

126
00:06:37,224 --> 00:06:39,065
progress and representing the emotion of the human

127
00:06:39,105 --> 00:06:41,105
experience in games like Gone Home and The Beginner's Guide

128
00:06:41,125 --> 00:06:44,606
and so on, we as developers can't ignore the physical

129
00:06:44,686 --> 00:06:47,407
aspects of what it's like to be human and these bodies that we

130
00:06:47,447 --> 00:06:49,728
inhabit, many parts fragile and resilient.

131
00:06:51,089 --> 00:06:51,669
So how do we do this?

132
00:06:52,189 --> 00:06:54,430
How can we better represent the vast range of human

133
00:06:54,450 --> 00:06:55,390
vitality in games?

134
00:06:56,090 --> 00:06:59,572
Well, the first thing to do is realize the many ways that

135
00:06:59,592 --> 00:07:01,092
health has already been represented in games.

136
00:07:01,862 --> 00:07:04,304
So here's where I finally get to mention that game that I'm

137
00:07:04,424 --> 00:07:08,366
making. So I've been working on Catacomb Kids for a while. It's

138
00:07:08,386 --> 00:07:10,907
a platformer roguelike with all the things you'd expect from a

139
00:07:10,947 --> 00:07:14,089
platformer roguelike. Procedurally generated levels,

140
00:07:17,291 --> 00:07:25,015
looting, dungeon crawling, you level up, permadeath. Is it not

141
00:07:25,055 --> 00:07:25,255
going?

142
00:07:29,092 --> 00:07:32,513
permadeath. It also has a fairly standard sort of health system,

143
00:07:33,194 --> 00:07:36,194
which is you have a certain amount of HP, when you get hit,

144
00:07:36,655 --> 00:07:40,396
that number goes down. When it is zero, you are dead. This is

145
00:07:40,436 --> 00:07:43,837
video games. If you were trying to represent a not video game,

146
00:07:43,877 --> 00:07:46,998
but you want to make it seem very video games, this is the

147
00:07:47,038 --> 00:07:49,419
thing that you do. Put some numbers or health bars

148
00:07:49,499 --> 00:07:53,660
overheads. It's an easy way to detach events from reality. So

149
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:55,541
this is what I'm going to call the first most basic way of

150
00:07:55,601 --> 00:07:57,921
representing health in games, which is through abstraction.

151
00:07:59,484 --> 00:08:01,425
People don't really have hit points.

152
00:08:01,665 --> 00:08:02,565
I'm sorry to disappoint you.

153
00:08:02,945 --> 00:08:04,746
You can't defeat your rude neighbor

154
00:08:04,806 --> 00:08:07,126
by repeatedly slapping him in the shin until he explodes.

155
00:08:08,407 --> 00:08:09,847
Abstraction of health can be convenient, though.

156
00:08:10,848 --> 00:08:12,588
It's easy to understand the cause and effect

157
00:08:12,648 --> 00:08:14,049
are immediate and readable.

158
00:08:14,389 --> 00:08:15,889
It lets players plan more effectively

159
00:08:15,929 --> 00:08:18,490
when they know that the boss's fireball does three damage

160
00:08:18,530 --> 00:08:20,491
and they have eight health, or when they know that, like,

161
00:08:20,631 --> 00:08:23,112
it takes six bullets to kill someone without body armor.

162
00:08:24,935 --> 00:08:28,298
and abstraction doesn't always only take on the form of hit points, abstraction can also be

163
00:08:28,318 --> 00:08:31,522
status effects in jrpgs, like oh no my strong dude got poisoned

164
00:08:31,882 --> 00:08:33,904
now a number is decreasing at regular intervals

165
00:08:35,045 --> 00:08:37,008
or dang my ice cream buddy got blinded

166
00:08:37,328 --> 00:08:40,251
now the percentage chance of a thing that i want to happen happening is

167
00:08:40,311 --> 00:08:41,332
significantly diminished

168
00:08:43,487 --> 00:08:45,948
I don't actually play a lot of JRPGs, sorry, with those examples, but...

169
00:08:46,488 --> 00:08:50,290
The point still stands that abstractions of health are basically those systems whereby

170
00:08:50,590 --> 00:08:53,371
players essentially lack all aspects of meatiness,

171
00:08:53,951 --> 00:08:55,712
maybe aside from that death is possible.

172
00:08:56,553 --> 00:08:59,734
They're not treated as a collection of parts, but as some inseparable whole

173
00:09:00,054 --> 00:09:02,255
where injury to any part is an injury to all parts.

174
00:09:03,376 --> 00:09:05,097
Neither are they fragile or resilient because

175
00:09:05,457 --> 00:09:07,578
both of those require some manner of meaningful change.

176
00:09:07,598 --> 00:09:09,118
To be fragile is to be breakable.

177
00:09:09,459 --> 00:09:11,540
To be resilient is to be restored from brokenness.

178
00:09:12,587 --> 00:09:18,369
With abstracted health systems, player characters are mechanically identical at both one health and 100.

179
00:09:19,089 --> 00:09:24,451
Or, if there is some mechanical change, it will have no resemblance to the actuality of being human.

180
00:09:24,951 --> 00:09:25,691
Mario, for instance.

181
00:09:26,592 --> 00:09:29,133
In the 2D Mario games, most of them, you can get up to three hit points.

182
00:09:29,313 --> 00:09:32,854
One for your outfit, one for your bigness, and the last one to kill you.

183
00:09:34,156 --> 00:09:37,239
that doesn't sound remotely human. One for your outfit, one

184
00:09:37,299 --> 00:09:40,442
for your bigness, and the last one to kill you? Like what is

185
00:09:40,482 --> 00:09:45,708
that? Do people shrink? No, that doesn't happen. Another way to

186
00:09:45,728 --> 00:09:48,270
look at it is this. Another way to look at it is this.

187
00:09:49,248 --> 00:09:52,831
If you can represent the player character as a ball or some other abstract shape

188
00:09:53,231 --> 00:09:56,573
and still have the health system make just as much or just as little sense

189
00:09:57,033 --> 00:09:59,174
it's probably using an abstract representation of health

190
00:09:59,555 --> 00:10:02,797
because there's not really an easy way to convert back and forth between people and balls

191
00:10:03,317 --> 00:10:06,819
If you can, it's hard to believe that anything resembling a human was part of the equation to begin with

192
00:10:08,102 --> 00:10:10,244
Of course, abstraction is far from the only way

193
00:10:10,345 --> 00:10:12,627
human physicality can and has been represented in games.

194
00:10:13,107 --> 00:10:14,469
There are many games that have tried to employ

195
00:10:14,489 --> 00:10:15,530
more representative systems.

196
00:10:16,151 --> 00:10:17,692
And one of those games that really opened my eyes

197
00:10:17,712 --> 00:10:19,915
to the possibilities was a roguelike called Ivan.

198
00:10:20,956 --> 00:10:23,138
A few years ago, I was working on Catacomb Kids

199
00:10:23,198 --> 00:10:24,640
and it was undergoing a major rewrite

200
00:10:24,660 --> 00:10:26,882
because, you know, solo indie game dev,

201
00:10:26,942 --> 00:10:28,123
I like redoing things.

202
00:10:29,324 --> 00:10:30,846
And at the time, I was playing quite a bit of Ivan.

203
00:10:31,706 --> 00:10:34,447
which is sort of a comedic traditional roguelike.

204
00:10:34,467 --> 00:10:36,068
It's got this weird banana theme going on.

205
00:10:36,088 --> 00:10:37,749
It doesn't take itself very seriously at all.

206
00:10:38,249 --> 00:10:39,289
But I was really taken by the health

207
00:10:39,309 --> 00:10:40,170
and damage system in the game.

208
00:10:41,290 --> 00:10:42,511
So this is a screenshot of the game.

209
00:10:42,531 --> 00:10:44,311
It's like, you know, looks like a roguelike.

210
00:10:44,331 --> 00:10:46,172
It's got the tiles and the description at the bottom.

211
00:10:46,532 --> 00:10:48,113
And over at the side, you can see all your stats.

212
00:10:48,653 --> 00:10:51,314
And up at the top, there's like a little representation

213
00:10:51,354 --> 00:10:51,894
of your character.

214
00:10:53,255 --> 00:10:55,596
And in Ivan, the player's body is separated

215
00:10:55,616 --> 00:10:56,757
into seven different areas.

216
00:10:57,117 --> 00:10:59,838
Head, body, groin, left and right arm,

217
00:11:00,078 --> 00:11:00,658
left and right leg.

218
00:11:01,595 --> 00:11:03,056
each of which has its own pool of HP.

219
00:11:03,757 --> 00:11:05,738
And alongside this is a more, you know,

220
00:11:05,979 --> 00:11:07,880
common abstracted health system where you die

221
00:11:07,900 --> 00:11:09,222
if your total HP reaches zero,

222
00:11:09,602 --> 00:11:13,926
but each limb, like if your arm reaches zero health,

223
00:11:14,266 --> 00:11:15,187
it'll get cut off.

224
00:11:15,307 --> 00:11:17,028
If your legs, you can get your legs cut off

225
00:11:17,109 --> 00:11:19,090
and if your body takes too much damage,

226
00:11:19,110 --> 00:11:20,972
then you'll die regardless of what your total

227
00:11:21,012 --> 00:11:22,333
remaining health pool is.

228
00:11:24,915 --> 00:11:25,976
Same with your head and your groin.

